## Introduction  
The **County Board Of Supervisors** (often abbreviated to *Board of Supervisors* or, for short, *the folks who pretend they’re not just a glorified committee of bureaucrats*) is the legislative backbone of most U.S. counties. Think of it as the political equivalent of a reality‑TV show: everyone thinks they’re the star, but the script is written by the county clerk, the budget office, and an ever‑growing stack of zoning ordinances. In the grand American experiment of “local self‑government,” the Board of Supervisors is the part that decides whether your neighbor’s chicken coop becomes a “home‑based business” or a “public nuisance,” all while delivering earnest speeches about “community engagement” that sound suspiciously like a TED Talk on how to make people care about a budget line item titled *“Roads – Pothole Repair (Phase 2).”*  

